            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this insulation calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This insulation calculator helps you plan residential or light
                commercial insulation projects by estimating:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Total area to insulate (net of large openings)</li>
                <li>Estimated R‑value based on material and thickness</li>
                <li>
                  How many batts, rolls, or bags you need, including a waste
                  factor
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Area calculation</h3>
              <p>For each rectangular section you enter, the area is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Imperial:</strong> Area (ft²) = Length (ft) × Width
                  (ft)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Metric:</strong> Area (m²) = Length (m) × Width (m)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator then subtracts the area of any openings you add:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Net insulated area = Σ Areas − Σ Openings</p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. R‑value estimation</h3>
              <p>
                R‑value is a measure of thermal resistance. Higher R‑values mean
                better insulation. For most materials, R‑value is roughly
                proportional to thickness:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Total R ≈ (R per inch) × Thickness (inches)</p>
              </div>
              <p>Typical approximate values used in this tool (per inch):</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Fiberglass batt / roll: <strong>R‑3.2 to R‑3.7</strong> (we
                  use 3.4)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Fiberglass blown: <strong>R‑2.2 to R‑2.9</strong> (we use 2.7)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Cellulose blown: <strong>R‑3.2 to R‑3.8</strong> (we use 3.5)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Mineral wool batt: <strong>R‑3.7 to R‑4.3</strong> (we use
                  4.0)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Spray foam (open‑cell): <strong>R‑3.5 to R‑3.8</strong> (we
                  use 3.7)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Spray foam (closed‑cell): <strong>R‑6.0 to R‑7.0</strong> (we
                  use 6.5)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Actual R‑values depend on the specific product and installation
                quality. Always verify with the manufacturer’s data sheet or
                packaging.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Package quantity</h3>
              <p>
                Once the net area is known, the calculator applies your waste
                factor and divides by the coverage per package:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Adjusted area = Net area × (1 + Waste % / 100)</p>
                <p>Packages needed = Adjusted area ÷ Coverage per package</p>
                <p>
                  Final result is rounded <strong>up</strong> to the next whole
                  package.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Typical recommended R‑values (U.S.)</h2>
              <p>
                Exact requirements depend on your climate zone and local energy
                code, but common recommendations are:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Attic / roof:</strong> R‑38 to R‑60</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>2×4 above‑grade walls:</strong> R‑13 to R‑15 cavity,
                  plus possible exterior continuous insulation
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>2×6 above‑grade walls:</strong> R‑19 to R‑21 cavity
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Floors over unconditioned space:</strong> R‑25 to R‑30
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Basement walls:</strong> R‑10 to R‑15 continuous, or
                  R‑13 to R‑19 cavity
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Check your local building department or energy‑efficiency
                program for the exact values in your region.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for sizing insulation</h2>
              <h3>Account for waste and off‑cuts</h3>
              <p>
                Insulation projects almost always generate waste from trimming
                around framing, electrical boxes, and odd shapes. A waste factor
                of <strong>5–15%</strong> is typical for batts and rolls;
                blown‑in insulation may have slightly lower waste if installed
                carefully.
              </p>

              <h3>Don’t compress batts</h3>
              <p>
                Batts are designed for a specific cavity depth. For example, an
                R‑19 fiberglass batt is typically made for a 6¼‑inch 2×6 cavity.
                Compressing an R‑19 batt into a 3½‑inch 2×4 cavity does
                <em>not</em> give you R‑19; the total R‑value drops because the
                thickness is reduced.
              </p>

              <h3>Layering insulation</h3>
              <p>
                You can layer different insulation types. In series, R‑values
                are approximately additive:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Total R ≈ R<sub>layer1</sub> + R<sub>layer2</sub> + …</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For example, R‑13 batts between joists plus R‑30 blown
                insulation on top yields roughly R‑43, assuming no compression
                and good coverage.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The tool assumes flat, rectangular areas and uniform
                  thickness.
                </li>
                <li>
                  R‑values are approximate averages; always confirm with product
                  data.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Moisture control, air sealing, and ventilation are
                  <strong>not</strong> modeled but are critical to performance
                  and durability.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Building codes may require specific installation methods, fire
                  ratings, and vapor control layers.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>How do I calculate how much insulation I need?</h3>
              <p>
                Measure the length and width of each area, multiply to get
                square footage (or square meters), subtract large openings, and
                divide by the coverage per batt, roll, or bag listed on the
                product label. This calculator automates those steps and adds a
                waste factor.
              </p>

              <h3>What R‑value should I aim for?</h3>
              <p>
                Use the “Target R‑value” field to compare your planned thickness
                and material to typical recommendations. If the estimated
                R‑value is below your target, increase thickness, choose a
                higher‑R material, or add another layer.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for both new construction and retrofits?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. For new construction, use framing dimensions to estimate
                area. For retrofits, measure accessible surfaces (attic floor,
                basement walls, etc.). For existing insulation, you can estimate
                its R‑value and add it to the new layer’s R‑value.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Is this calculator a substitute for code compliance design?
              </h3>
