enings you add: Net insulated area = Σ Areas − Σ Openings 2. R‑value estimation R‑value is a measure of thermal resistance. Higher R‑values mean better insulation. For most materials, R‑value is roughly proportional to thickness: Total R ≈ (R per inch) × Thickness (inches) Typical approximate values used in this tool (per inch): Fiberglass batt / roll: R‑3.2 to R‑3.7 (we use 3.4) Fiberglass blown: R‑2.2 to R‑2.9 (we use 2.7) Cellulose blown: R‑3.2 to R‑3.8 (we use 3.5) Mineral wool batt: R‑3.7 to R‑4.3 (we use 4.0) Spray foam (open‑cell): R‑3.5 to R‑3.8 (we use 3.7) Spray foam (closed‑cell): R‑6.0 to R‑7.0 (we use 6.5) Actual R‑values depend on the specific product and installation quality. Always verify with the manufacturer’s data sheet or packaging. 3. Package quantity Once the net area is known, the calculator applies your waste factor and divides by the coverage per package: Adjusted area = Net area × (1 + Waste % / 100) Packages needed = Adjusted area ÷ Coverage per package Final result is rounded up to the next whole package. Typical recommended R‑values (U.S.) Exact requirements depend on your climate zone and local energy code, but common recommendations are: Attic / roof: R‑38 to R‑60 2×4 above‑grade walls: R‑13 to R‑15 cavity, plus possible exterior continuous insulation 2×6 above‑grade walls: R‑19 to R‑21 cavity Floors over unconditioned space: R‑25 to R‑30 Basement walls: R‑10 to R‑15 continuous, or R‑13 to R‑19 cavity Check your local building department or energy‑efficiency program for the exact values in your region. Practical tips for sizing insulation Account for waste and off‑cuts Insulation projects almost always generate waste from trimming around framing, electrical boxes, and odd shapes. A waste factor of 5–15% is typical for batts and rolls; blown‑in insulation may have slightly lower waste if installed carefully. Don’t compress batts Batts are designed for a specific cavity depth. For example, an R‑19 fiberglass batt is typically made for a 