thickness How many batts, rolls, or bags you need, including a waste factor 1. Area calculation For each rectangular section you enter, the area is: Imperial: Area (ft²) = Length (ft) × Width (ft) Metric: Area (m²) = Length (m) × Width (m) The calculator then subtracts the area of any openings you add: Net insulated area = Σ Areas − Σ Openings 2. R‑value estimation R‑value is a measure of thermal resistance. Higher R‑values mean better insulation. For most materials, R‑value is roughly proportional to thickness: Total R ≈ (R per inch) × Thickness (inches) Typical approximate values used in this tool (per inch): Fiberglass batt / roll: R‑3.2 to R‑3.7 (we use 3.4) Fiberglass blown: R‑2.2 to R‑2.9 (we use 2.7) Cellulose blown: R‑3.2 to R‑3.8 (we use 3.5) Mineral wool batt: R‑3.7 to R‑4.3 (we use 4.0) Spray foam (open‑cell): R‑3.5 to R‑3.8 (we use 3.7) Spray foam (closed‑cell): R‑6.0 to R‑7.0 (we use 6.5) Actual R‑values depend on the specific product and installation quality. Always verify with the manufacturer’s data sheet or packaging. 3. Package quantity Once the net area is known, the calculator applies your waste factor and divides by the coverage per package: Adjusted area = Net area × (1 + Waste % / 100) Packages needed = Adjusted area ÷ Coverage per package Final result is rounded up to the next whole package. Typical recommended R‑values (U.S.) Exact requirements depend on your climate zone and local energy code, but common recommendations are: Attic / roof: R‑38 to R‑60 2×4 above‑grade walls: R‑13 to R‑15 cavity, plus possible exterior continuous insulation 2×6 above‑grade walls: R‑19 to R‑21 cavity Floors over unconditioned space: R‑25 to R‑30 Basement walls: R‑10 to R‑15 continuous, or R‑13 to R‑19 cavity Check your local building department or energy‑efficiency program for the exact values in your region. Practical tips for sizing insulation Account for waste and off‑cuts Insulation projects almost always generate waste from trimming around framing, electrical boxes, and odd shapes. A waste factor of 5–15% is typical for batts and rolls; blown‑in insulation may have slightly lower waste if installed carefully. Don’t compress batts Batts are designed for a specific cavity depth. For example, an R‑19 fiberglass batt is typically made for a 6¼‑inch 2×6 cavity. Compressing an R‑19 batt into a 3½‑inch 2×4 cavity does not give you R‑19; the total R‑value drops because the thickness is reduced. Layering insulation You can layer different insulation types. In series, R‑values are approximately additive: Total R ≈ R layer1 + R layer2 + … For example, R‑13 batts between joists plus R‑30 blown insulation on top yields roughly R‑43, assuming no compression and good coverage. Limitations and assumptions The tool assumes flat, rectangular areas and uniform thickness. R‑values are approximate averages; always confirm with product data. Moisture control, air sealing, and ventilation are not modeled but are critical to performance and durability. Building codes may require specific installation methods, fire ratings, and vapor control layers. Frequently asked questions How do I calculate how much insulation I need? Measure the length and width of each area, multiply to get square footage (or square meters), subtract large openings, and divide by the coverage per batt, roll, or bag listed on the product label. This calculator automates those steps and adds a waste factor. What R‑value should I aim for? Use the “Target R‑value” field to compare your planned thickness and material to typical recommendations. If the estimated R‑value is below your target, increase thickness, choose a higher‑R material, or add another layer. Can I use this for both new construction and retrofits? Yes. For new construction, use framing dimensions to estimate area. For retrofits, measure accessible surfaces (attic floor, basement walls, etc.). For existing insulation, you can estimate its R‑value and add it to the new layer’s R‑value. Is this calculator a s